	abstract = {Background  There is a growing recognition that sex characteristics and gender-related aspects can have a substantial impact on the health-related quality of life ({HRQoL}) of persons with Parkinson’s disease ({PD}). Gender is a multidimensional construct, including dynamic social norms and relations that influence health and impact quality of life. Even when gender is investigated in the field of {PD}, it is frequently conceptualized as gender identity while other dimensions, such as roles or relations, are generally ignored. The aim of this study was to explore the impact of several gender dimensions on {HRQoL} among people with {PD}.
